{
  "text": "Previous studies in a model of hypertensive small vessel injury have demonstrated that increases in pressure within capillaries can cause endothelial cell injury and platelet accumulation [CITATION_1] . However, in the present study, despite a presumed rapid increase in glomerular capillary pressure P, there were few ultrastructural indications of glomerular cell damage prior to, or at the time of, the induction of proliferation. In contrast to the lack of significant ultrastructural evidence for glomerular endothelial or epithelial damage, rare intracapillary platelet accumulations were detected one week after 5/6 nephrectomy in a minority of glomeruli, suggesting that the increased shear stress in the glomerular capillaries of these rats led to alterations of the antithrombotic properties of the capillary walls.",
  "citation_candidates": [
